The start symbol S always expands to two nonterminals (S → NT5 NT2), and there are no ε‐productions. Hence any generated string has length ≥2. Since "t25" is length 1, it cannot be generated.  
No

To generate a single terminal from this grammar in CNF, S would need a direct production S → 't23', or via a chain of unit productions leading to a terminal. But no such unit or direct terminal rule exists for S, and all S-productions expand to two nonterminals. Thus S cannot derive a single terminal. 

No

We have S → NT5 NT2.  
Checking terminal productions:  
• NT5 → ‘t25’  
• NT2 → ‘t23’  

Thus S ⇒ NT5 NT2 ⇒ ‘t25’ ‘t23’, so the grammar generates the string.  
Yes

We need S ⇒ NT5 NT2, and to get exactly two terminals NT5 must go directly to a terminal and NT2 likewise. NT2 can produce ‘t9’, but NT5’s only terminal productions are ‘t18’, ‘t23’, ‘t25’, or ‘t13’ (no ‘t12’). Hence NT5 cannot yield ‘t12’, so the grammar cannot generate “t12 t9.”  
No

To decide if “t12 t12” is in L(G), run the CYK algorithm:

1.  For each position i=1,2, list the nonterminals that produce the terminal wi = t12:
    – NT3 → t12  
    – NT6 → t12  
    So cell (1,1) = {NT3, NT6}, and cell (2,1) = {NT3, NT6}.

2.  Now for the span of length 2 (cells (1,2)), look for any binary rule A → B C with B in cell (1,1) and C in cell (2,1). The only match is  
    NT2 → NT3 NT6  
    since NT3∈cell(1,1) and NT6∈cell(2,1).  
    Hence cell (1,2) = {NT2}.

3.  Finally, to derive the entire string from the start symbol S, we’d need S ∈ cell(1,2). But the only production for S is  
    S → NT5 NT2  
    which requires NT5 in cell(1,1) (it isn’t) and NT2 in cell(2,1) (it isn’t). So S does not appear in cell (1,2).

Therefore “t12 t12” cannot be derived from S. 

No

To generate a two‐token string, S → NT5 NT2 must expand with NT5 ⇒ one terminal and NT2 ⇒ one terminal.  
  
1) Can NT5 ⇒ ‘t34’?  
   No – NT5’s terminal rules are only ‘t18’, ‘t23’, ‘t25’, ‘t13’.  

2) Can NT2 ⇒ ‘t6’?  
   No – NT2’s terminal rules are ‘t9’, ‘t23’, ‘t27’, ‘t30’, ‘t4’.  

Since neither position can match, the grammar cannot generate “t34 t6.”  
No

To generate a 2‐token string from S → NT5 NT2, each of NT5 and NT2 must produce exactly one terminal. NT2 can produce t9 (via NT2 → 't9'), but NT5’s only terminal productions are 't18', 't23', 't25', and 't13'. There is no way for NT5 to yield 't24' as a single terminal, and any other expansion of NT5 would produce more than one token. Therefore the grammar cannot generate “t24 t9.”  
No

To derive a 4‐token string S⇒NT5 NT2, NT2 must cover the last 1–2 tokens and NT5 the first 2–3.  Checking both splits fails:

1) Split 3+1 (NT5⇒3 tokens, NT2⇒1 token=t12): NT2 has no rule NT2→t12.

2) Split 2+2 (NT5⇒t23 t27; NT2⇒t23 t12 via NT2→NT3 NT6, NT3→t23, NT6→t12).  
   But NT5 must derive “t23 t27” by NT5→NT0 NT5, so NT0→t23 (impossible) or NT5→t23 (then no slot to get t27).

No valid parse exists.  
No

We need S ⇒ NT5 NT2 to yield “t27 t23 t27 t12.”  Since NT5 can only produce a nonempty string ending in one of {t18, t25, t13}, the boundary between NT5 and NT2 must lie right after one of those three terminals.  But in our target string the only possible splits are

•  t27 | t23 t27 t12  
•  t27 t23 | t27 t12  
•  t27 t23 t27 | t12

and none of the first‐parts ends in t18, t25 or t13.  Hence NT5 NT2 cannot yield “t27 t23 t27 t12.”  

Answer: No

After examining the productions for NT5:

NT5 → NT0 NT5 | 't18' | 't23' | 't25' | 't13'

any string derived from NT5 either

1. has length 1 and is one of {t18, t23, t25, t13}, or  
2. has length ≥ 2, in which case its first terminal comes from NT0.

NT0 can only produce {t24, t27, t13, t6, t30, t31, t14, t9, t34}, none of which is t10.

Thus NT5 can never begin with t10, so S → NT5 NT2 cannot yield a string starting with t10. The given string t10 t34 t7 t31 is not in the language.

No

To generate 4 tokens from S→NT5 NT2, NT5 must produce at least 1 and NT2 at least 1, so NT5 can cover positions 1…i and NT2 covers i+1…4.  Checking all splits:

1) i=1: NT5 must produce “t9” – but NT5’s only terminals are t18, t23, t25, t13.  Impossible.

2) i=2: NT5⇒NT0 NT5 gives tokens (t9, t28).  NT0 can give t9, but NT5’s terminal cannot be t28.

3) i=3: NT5⇒NT0 NT0 NT5 gives tokens (t9, t28, t14).  NT0 can only give from {t24,t27,t13,t6,t30,t31,t14,t9}, so the second NT0 can’t give t28, and the final NT5 terminal cannot be t14.

No split works, so S cannot derive “t9 t28 t14 t10.”  
No

After running a CYK‐style check, no nonterminal can cover any length‐2 span, so no larger spans can be built. In particular S → NT5 NT2 cannot cover a 5‐token string. 

No

We can split the target 6‐token string as

   t18   |  t20 t23 t27 t13 t9  
   ————   ——————————————
    NT5          NT2

1. NT5 ⇒ 't18' is a valid terminal rule.  
2. NT2 ⇒ NT3 NT6.  
   - NT3 ⇒ 't20' is allowed.  
   - We must have NT6 ⇒ t23 t27 t13 t9.  
     NT6 can expand as  
       NT6 ⇒ NT4 NT6 ⇒ NT4 NT6 ⇒ NT4 NT6 ⇒ 't9'  
       (i.e. two NT4 blocks then a final terminal 't9').  
     Choose  
       first NT4 ⇒ 't23'  
       second NT4 ⇒ NT2 NT5 ⇒ 't27' 't13'  
       final NT6 ⇒ 't9'  
     which yields exactly t23 t27 t13 t9.

Thus S ⇒ NT5 NT2 ⇒ t18 (NT3 NT6) ⇒ t18 t20 t23 t27 t13 t9.  
Yes

After running a CYK parse (and checking the only possible S→NT5 NT2 splits), you find no way to cover “t1 t18 t30 t13 t23 t1.” In particular, NT2 cannot generate the final t1 in a consistent two‐symbol expansion, nor can it match it as a single terminal. Hence the string is not in L(G).

No

After attempting all possible splits and applying the CNF productions via CYK‐style reasoning, there is no way to derive the string t8 t13 t11 t13 t10 t4 from S.  
No

The grammar can generate the string as follows.  Set aside the final symbol t30 and let NT2 → t30.  That leaves the six‐symbol prefix

  t27  t14  t24  t9  t34  t25

to be produced by NT5.  NT5 can unroll five times via

  NT5 → NT0 NT5 → NT0 NT0 NT5 → … → NT0⁵ NT5

and then terminate with the base rule NT5 → t25.  Each NT0 → one of {t27, t14, t24, t9, t34} in order.  Finally S → NT5 NT2 yields

  (t27 t14 t24 t9 t34 t25) (t30).

Hence the string is in the language.  Yes

To see it more directly:

1. NT5 ⇒ NT0 NT5 ⇒ NT0 NT0 NT5 ⇒ NT0 NT0 NT0 NT5 ⇒ NT0 NT0 NT0 NT0 NT5  
   – choosing NT0 → t30, t27, t13, t13 in order  
   – and the final NT5 → t25  
   yields t30 t27 t13 t13 t25.

2. NT2 → NT3 NT6  
   – choose NT3 → t20 and NT6 → t25  
   yields t20 t25.

3. Finally S → NT5 NT2 concatenates those two pieces into  
   t30 t27 t13 t13 t25 t20 t25.

Hence the grammar does generate the string.  
Yes

After running the CYK‐style check (or else noting that S→NT5 NT2 forces NT2 to cover the last 1–2 tokens and NT5 to cover the rest, and that NT5’s final terminal must be one of {t18,t23,t25,t13} which does not match the fifth token t27), you cannot derive

  t31 t8 t9 t4 t27 t24 t25

from S. 

No

We need to end with “Yes” or “No.”  
The start rule is S → NT5 NT2. The given string has 7 terminals, so NT5 must derive 5 or 6 terminals and NT2 must derive 2 or 1.  

1) If NT2 derives 1 terminal (via a rule NT2 → t9 | t23 | t27 | t30), it would have to match the final terminal t14 – it doesn’t.  
2) If NT2 derives 2 terminals (via NT2 → NT3 NT6), those would have to be the last two, t10 t14. NT3 has no rule for t10, so that fails too.  

No other split is possible, so the grammar cannot generate  
“t27 t12 t1 t34 t23 t10 t14.”  

No

To see that S ⇒ NT5 NT2 can produce your string t13 t9 t30 t14 t24 t13 t28 t9, split off the last two symbols for NT2 and make the first six for NT5.

1. NT2 ⇒ NT3 NT6 ⇒ t28 t9, since NT3→t28 and NT6→t9.
2. NT5 ⇒ NT0 NT5 ⇒ NT0 NT0 NT5 ⇒ ⋯ (5 times) ⋯ ⇒ NT0 NT5 ⇒ t13 (via the terminal rule NT5→t13), with each of the first five NT0→ one of t13,t9,t30,t14,t24.

That yields exactly t13 t9 t30 t14 t24 t13 for NT5 and t28 t9 for NT2, so S ⇒ NT5 NT2 ⇒ your string. Yes

After running the CYK algorithm, we find a valid parse:

1) S ⇒ NT5 NT2 covering positions 1–6 and 7–8.  
2) NT5 ⇒ NT0 NT5 five times, spawning NT0 at positions 1…5 and finally NT5 ⇒ ‘t18’ at position 6, with each NT0 ⇒ the terminals t34,t14,t31,t13,t9 in order.  
3) NT2 ⇒ NT3 NT6 with NT3 ⇒ ‘t29’ at position 7 and NT6 ⇒ ‘t25’ at position 8.

Thus the string t34 t14 t31 t13 t9 t18 t29 t25 is in the language.  

Yes

After attempting all possible splits for S → NT5 NT2 (with NT2 either a terminal or NT3 NT6), the seventh symbol t11 cannot be generated by NT5 (its terminal rules are only t18, t23, t25, t13) nor by NT3 in NT2 → NT3 NT6 (NT3’s terminals do not include t11). Hence the string cannot be derived. 

No

After running a CYK‐style fill on the 8 tokens, no cell (1,8) ever contains S. In particular you’d need S→NT5 NT2 but no split gives NT5 on the left and NT2 on the right. So the answer is:

No

We can split the 9‐symbol string as

  S → NT5  NT2  
  NT5 ⇒ t31 t9 t14 t13 t24 t9 t9 t13  (length 8)  
  NT2 ⇒ t4                           (length 1)

Check that NT5 can indeed generate the 8‐symbol prefix: each of t31,t9,t14,t13,t24,t9,t9 comes from NT0, and the final t13 is one of NT5’s terminal productions.  
And NT2 → 't4' is directly allowed.  
Hence the full string is in the language.  

Yes

After running a CYK‐style fill‐in, you find no way to get S over the full 9 tokens.  Equivalently, checking the shape S→NT5 NT2 shows neither of the two length‐partition cases can match the given terminals.  Hence the string is not in the language.  

No

To generate a string, S→NT5 NT2.  
NT5 can only produce a non‐empty string whose last terminal is one of {t18,t23,t25,t13}, and NT2 must then produce the remainder.  
Our input tokens are  
  t24, t28, t30, t34, t28, t20, t34, t30, t28  
None of these is in {t18,t23,t25,t13}, so NT5 cannot match any non‐empty prefix of the input.  
Hence S cannot derive the string.  

No

After running the CYK algorithm on the 10‐token input, the start symbol S never appears in the full-span cell T[1,10].  Hence the string is not in the language.  

No

After running a CYK‐style check, one finds no way to split the 10‐token input so that the left part is in NT5 and the right part in NT2 (nor can NT2 alone derive the required suffix). Therefore the string is not in the language.  
No

After running the CYK‐style filling of the table, you find that no way exists to split the 10 tokens so that S→NT5 NT2 covers all of them (in particular NT2 never covers the final token “t28”).  Hence the string is not in the language.  

No

After trying both ways of splitting S into NT5 … NT2 (with NT2 generating either one or two terminals) and checking how NT5 must expand (it would have to end in one of t18, t23, t25, or t13 to match your 9th token), no valid derivation exists. 

No

After examining the possible splits S→NT5 NT2, the only way NT2 can end in t27 is by the unary rule NT2→'t27' (i.e. a length‐1 suffix).  That forces NT5 to generate the first 10 tokens  
t18 t24 t28 t20 t6 t5 t34 t29 t11 t11  
—but NT5 cannot generate t11 at positions 9–10 (NT5 only ever emits terminals from {t18,t23,t25,t13} once its recursion bottoms out).  Hence no derivation matches the full 11‐token string.  
No

After running the CYK‐style filling, the only nonempty cells beyond the single‐terminals were

(1–2): NT6  
(8–9): NT2  

No combination ever produces NT5 on a left subspan and NT2 on the complementary right subspan covering the whole 1–13 range. In particular S → NT5 NT2 never appears spanning 1–13. 

Hence the grammar does not generate the given string.

No

After checking every possible split S→NT5 NT2 (with NT2 either a single terminal or NT3 NT6) against the 13‐token string, no assignment of the suffix to NT2 works (the final token t8 isn’t a direct NT2 terminal, and every candidate NT3 start fails to have all intervening tokens in NT4 before ending in an NT6 token). Therefore the string is not in the language.  
No

After running the CYK‐style fill‐in, one finds that no way exists to build S ⇒* the 14‐token string. In particular, S → NT5 NT2 would force NT2 to cover the last block (but no NT2 expansion can match the tail “t13 t8 …” properly), and no combination of the binary rules ever fills in the table cell [1,14] with S. Hence the string is not in the language.  

No

After trying every possible split of the 14‐token input into a NT5‐generated prefix and a NT2‐generated suffix, no partition meets both

 1. NT5’s requirement that its final token be one of {t18,t23,t25,t13}, and  
 2. NT2→NT3 NT6’s requirement that NT6’s final token lie in {t8,t25,t12,t29,t22,t9,t18,t10}.  

The only way NT2 could cover the last token t27 is via its terminal rule NT2→'t27', but that forces NT5 to end in t8 (position 13), which NT5 cannot do. Hence the string is not in the language.  

No

To be generated by S, the final 1–2 terminals must come from NT2 (since S → NT5 NT2).  NT2 either produces a single terminal (one of t9,t27,t23,t4,t30) or two terminals via NT3 NT6.  But our string ends “t6 t11”:

· NT2→terminal cannot yield t6 or t11.  
· NT2→NT3 NT6 would require NT3⇒t6 (NT3 cannot) or NT6⇒t6 (NT6 cannot).  

Hence NT2 cannot generate “t6 t11,” so S cannot generate the full string.  
No

To generate any string, S must split into NT5 … NT2.  However NT5 can only derive single terminals {t18,t23,t25,t13} (it never covers more than one symbol), and none of those appears at the very first position (t10).  Hence there is no way to match the entire input under S→NT5 NT2. 

No

To derive the string from S we would need S ⇒ NT5 NT2, so the very first terminal of the string must come from NT5.  But NT5 can only produce terminals in {t18, t23, t25, t13} (or via NT0 as its leftmost symbol, and NT0 never produces t10).  Since our string begins with t10, NT5 cannot generate that prefix.  Hence the grammar cannot generate the given string.  
No

After checking all possible splits of the 15‐token string into an NT5‐generated prefix and an NT2‐generated suffix—and examining every way NT2 can derive a suffix of length 1 through 14—none of them match the required terminals (especially the final token t14, which NT6 can never produce). Hence the string is not in the language. 

No

After trying every possible way to split the 15‐symbol string between NT5 (the left part) and NT2 (the right part) and then checking whether NT2 can generate its suffix via its single‐terminal rules or via NT3 NT6, we find that no split allows NT2 to match its portion.  Hence the full string cannot be derived from S.  

No

After examining the productions, the start symbol S always ends in an NT2 subtree.  NT2 can either directly emit one terminal (from {t9,t23,t27,t4,t30}) or go NT2→NT3 NT6, in which case the very last terminal comes from NT6.  But NT6’s terminal‐rules are {t8,t25,t12,t29,t22,t9,t18,t10}, none of which is t28.  No other nonterminal can produce t28 at the string’s end.  Hence the grammar cannot generate a string ending in t28.  

Answer: No

To derive S → NT5 NT2, the first token of any generated string must come from NT5.  NT5 can either:
1) terminate immediately as one of its terminal productions {t18, t23, t25, t13}, or  
2) expand via NT5 → NT0 NT5, in which case the first token comes from NT0’s terminals {t24, t27, t13, t6, t30, t31, t14, t9, t34}.

In no case can NT5 begin with t4.  But the given string begins with t4, so it cannot be generated.

No

After inspecting the possible derivations of S → NT5 NT2, one sees that NT5 can only start with tokens from NT0’s inventory {t24,t27,t13,t6,t30,t31,t14,t9,t34} and must end its prefix with a token from NT5’s own terminals {t18,t23,t25,t13}. But the very first token of the string is t5, which is in neither set, so NT5 cannot generate any non‐empty prefix starting with t5. Hence the string cannot be derived. 

No

After running a CYK‐style check, one finds that no valid split lets S ⇒ NT5 NT2 cover all 16 terminals. In particular, the NT6 recursion stalls around position 8 (no NT4 or NT6 can cover the token t24 in that context), so S cannot derive the full string. 

No

We need S ⇒ NT5 NT2; so the string splits into a prefix from NT5 and a suffix from NT2.  NT5 only produces strings of the form (NT0)ⁿ tX where tX∈{t18,t23,t25,t13}, and NT2 expands as NT3 NT6 (possibly with further recursion in NT6) or directly to a single terminal.

Scan the 17‐token string positions:

1: t18  
2: t4  
3: t34  
4: t31  
5: t23  
6: t27  
7: t18  
8: t28

12: t20  
13: t18

15: t25  
16: t1  
17: t9  

Any split point k (1≤k<17) must satisfy

– p[k]∈{t18,t23,t25,t13} (the NT5 base),  
– p[k+1]∈NT3’s terminals={t27,t29,t12,t1,t28,t20,t23,t24},  
– p[1..k−1] all in NT0’s terminals={t24,t27,t13,t6,t30,t31,t14,t9,t34},  
– p[k+2..17] generated by NT6 (a sequence of NT4‐terminals then one NT6‐terminal).

Testing the only viable k’s (where p[k] is in NT5’s base set and p[k+1] in NT3’s set) shows p[1] or p[1..k−1] always contains a token not in NT0, or p[k+1] not in NT3.  Hence no split yields a valid NT5-prefix/NT2-suffix decomposition.

Therefore the grammar cannot generate the given string.

After running the CYK‐style check, there is no way to split the 17‐token string into a NT5‐derived prefix and a NT2‐derived suffix so that S→NT5 NT2.  
Hence the grammar does *not* generate the string.

After trying all possible splits S→NT5 NT2, there is no way to let the prefix derive NT5 and the suffix derive NT2 (no NT2‐suffix can end in t14; the only viable NT2→NT3 NT6 split would start at position 4, but then the 3‐token prefix t28 t10 t11 cannot be NT5). Hence the string is not in L(G).

No

After attempting all possible splits S → NT5 NT2 and all NT2 expansions (both the direct‐terminal options and NT2 → NT3 NT6 with arbitrary NT6 recursion), no decomposition lets NT5 generate the required prefix and NT2 the required suffix. Hence the string is not in the language.

No

After attempting all possible top‐level splits S → NT5 NT2 (NT5 on a prefix ending in one of its terminals {t18,t23,t25,t13}, NT2 on the rest either by a single‐terminal rule or by NT3 NT6) one finds:

– The only viable prefix for NT5 is positions 1–2 (“t27 t23”), which works (NT5 → NT0 NT5 → t27·t23).  
– That forces NT2 to cover positions 3–18, so NT2 → NT3 NT6 with NT3→t23 at pos 3 and NT6 producing positions 4–18.  
– But NT6’s base terminals are {t8,t25,t29,t22,t12,t9,t18,t10}, and so any NT6 expansion must end in one of those. Here position 18 is t31, which NT6 cannot generate.  

No other split succeeds. Therefore the string is not in the language.

After running the CYK‐style fill‐in over the 18 tokens, no way emerges to split the string into a left NT5‐chunk and a right NT2‐chunk so as to satisfy

  S → NT5 NT2.

In particular, there is no span [1..k] whose table‐entry contains NT5 (and terminals for NT5 end only in {t18,t23,t25,t13}, but the prefixes ending there cannot all be NT0’s as required). Hence the start‐symbol S never appears covering the whole input.

Answer: No

To derive S→NT5 NT2, the prefix must be NT5.  NT5 generates exactly one of {t18,t23,t25,t13} at its last position, preceded by any number of NT0‐derived terminals.  Scanning the 19‐token string, only positions 11, 14 or 18 hold an NT5‐base terminal (t18), so those are the only possible NT5–NT2 splits:

  • Split at 11: tokens 1–10 would have to all be NT0‐terminals, but token 3 is t29 (NT0 cannot produce t29).  
  • Split at 14: tokens 1–13 would have to be NT0‐terminals, but token 3 is still t29.  
  • Split at 18: tokens 1–17 would have to be NT0‐terminals, yet token 3 fails again.  

No valid split works, so the grammar cannot generate the string.

That forces NT2 to cover tokens 2–19, but NT2 cannot derive that 18‐token suffix (NT2→terminal is too short and NT2→NT3 NT6 fails on the first symbol of the suffix). Hence no parse exists.

Therefore the grammar does not generate the given string.

After examining the allowed productions, any NT5‐derived prefix can only contain terminals from NT0’s set (t24, t27, t13, t6, t30, t31, t14, t9, t34) plus one final NT5 terminal (t18, t23, t25, t13). But the input has t5 at positions 4 and 15, and neither NT0 nor NT5 can ever produce t5. Any NT2‐derived suffix can introduce t5 only via NT6→NT4 NT6→t5…, but the very first symbol of the suffix must come from NT3 (if we use NT2→NT3 NT6), and NT3 cannot produce t5. There is no way to assign the t5’s at positions 4 and 15 to any nonterminal. Hence the grammar cannot generate this string.

We note that S ⇒ NT5 NT2, and NT5 can only generate strings of the form

  (NT0)^k  tX

where each NT0 ⇒ one of {t24,t27,t13,t6,t30,t31,t14,t9,t34} and tX ∈ {t18,t23,t25,t13}.  
In particular the very first token of any NT5-expansion must come from NT0’s list {24,27,13,6,30,31,14,9,34}, or, if NT5 produces only its terminal form, from {18,23,25,13}.  

But the input string begins with t28, which is not in either of those sets.  Hence no derivation can begin with t28, so the grammar cannot generate the given string.

No valid NT5 derivation exists, so the string cannot be generated by S → NT5 NT2.

  NT5 ⇒ t34 t9 t18  
and 
  NT2 ⇒ NT3 NT6 ⇒ t28 NT6 
so NT6 must cover the remaining 18 symbols t4…t25.  But no matter how you try to group that tail into NT6 → (NT4)… terminal – because at positions such as t6 or t24 the grammar cannot match NT4 or NT6 productions correctly – you fail to get a full derivation.  Thus the string is not in L(G).

After inspecting the productions for NT5:

• Any NT5 derivation of length ≥2 must begin with NT0→… to get its first terminal, yet NT0 cannot produce t4.  
• An NT5 derivation of length 1 must use NT5→'tX', but t4 is not one of NT5’s terminals.
